fields.descriptive_line: Dressed doll called Louisa, representing a young Caucasian girl, made by Bru in France ca. 1890
fields.physical_description:
Dressed bisque-headed doll with extra clothes.  The dress is in a very fashionable style of the 1880s for girls to wear, although the lace bonnet and the doll's mouth with the tongue between the lips are more suggestive of a baby.
[Doll] Doll representing a young Caucasian girl, with a wig of wavy blonde hair on a linen base over a cork pate, fixed inset eyes of white and blue glass with painted eyelashes beneath moulded and painted light brown brows, and an open but solid mouth with the tongue between the lips.  She has a bisque swivel head with moulded ears pierced for earrings (made from blue and green glass beads), and a bisque upper body; the rest of the body and the upper legs are of stiffened and padded cream kid.  The lower arms and hands are of bisque, with dimpled elbows; there is some degree of separation of all the fingers and thumbs, and the fingernails are indicated by moulding and pigment.  The lower legs and feet are of carved and painted wood, with the toes and toenails indicated; the doll is jointed at the shoulders, the elbows and the knees with metal headed pins, and has a small piece of adhesive cloth tape attached to the underside of each foot.
[Dress] Low-waisted princess-line short dress of dark bottle green satin lined throughout in white muslin, with a rounded lace edged neck; each of the elbow-length puffed sleeves finishes in a lace-edged cuff of brown and bronze-coloured brocade woven in a floral pattern.  The dress has a ruched central panel of the brown and bronze-coloured brocade, outlined in bronze-coloured braid, and with a sash of matching fabric trimmed with a bow of saffron yellow ribbon at the true right front; it is finished at the hem with an additional short pleated skirt of dark green satin over a band of pleated yellow ribbon and a flounce of white needle-run net.  The garment originally fastened at the back with four metal hooks and stitched loops.
[Petticoat] Lace-edged waist petticoat of white cotton gathered into a waistband of self fabric, fastening at the waist back with tying strings of white cotton tape
[Doll's clothing] Waist petticoat knitted in ivory-coloured wool using a rib stitch, with the welt in stocking stitch; the garment fastens at the waist with a drawstring of white cotton tape.
[Drawers] Lace-edged and pin-tucked drawers of white cotton, with a self fabric waistband and an open crotch.  The garment fastens at the back of the waist with a bound button and stitched buttonhole.
[Sock] Ankle sock of ivory-coloured cotton thread, knitted in a lacy pattern with a stocking stitch top and sole.
[Sock] Ankle sock of ivory-coloured cotton thread, knitted in a lacy pattern with a stocking stitch top and sole.
[Chemise] Sleeveless chemise of white cotton, with tucking at the front; the armholes and the placket neck are edged with lace, and the garment fastens at the neck with a bound button and stitched loop.
[Bonnet] Bonnet made up of strips of lace worked with a small floral sprig motif, the tatted circular crown with a cross motif at the centre.  The bonnet has a triple frill of lace edging around the face, and fastens beneath the chin with tying strings of pale pink ribbon.
[Shoe] Ankle-strap shoe of dark bronze-coloured leather with a cream-coloured twill lining and card insole, and a unit sole of undyed leather.  The vamp is decorated with a bow shape of leather beneath a metal buckle, and the shoe fastens at the ankle with a metal button and a stitched loop.
[Shoe] Ankle-strap shoe of dark bronze-coloured leather with a cream-coloured twill lining and card insole, and a unit sole of undyed leather.  The vamp is decorated with a bow shape of leather beneath a metal buckle, and the shoe originally fastened at the ankle with a metal button and a stitched loop.
[Doll's clothing] Dress of unlined cream flannel with a rounded neck and wrist-length sleeves, all edged with white lace; the skirt is gathered to the bodice at the waist, and finished with two horizontal tucks above the hem.  The garment fastens at the back of the bodice with three buttons and stitched loops.
[Doll's clothing] Yoked dress of unlined blue silk taffeta, with a rounded neck, Peter Pan collar and wrist-length sleeves.  The collar and hem are embroidered with French knots in pale pink silk thread, and the garment fastens at the back with two buttons and stitched loops.
[Doll's clothing] Dress of unlined white cotton piqué, with a rounded neck and wrist-length sleeves, all trimmed with white tatting.  The dress is tunic-shaped, with an additional pleated skirt added at the waist beneath a broad sash of self fabric which is attached at the front and stitched into a half bow at the back.  The garment fastens at the back with two buttons and stitched loops.
[Doll's clothing] Nightdress of white linen, with a drawstring neckline and straight wrist-length sleeves, all edged with lace.  The front of the garment is ruched at the waist front, and a tie belt of self fabric is attached at each side of the ruching; the garment fastens at the back with the neck drawstring and waist ties.
[Doll's clothing] Long tunic dress of unlined white cotton piqué printed with a pattern of small four-leaved sprigs in powder blue.  The garment has a rounded neck and puffed sleeves, all trimmed with white picot edging, and a frill of self fabric at the hem, and fastens at the back with a metal hook and a stitched loop.

fields.history_note: The doll, known as Louisa, was given by Miss F Ashbee (RF [19]61/1861). (Jane) Felicity Ashbee was born 22/02/1913 and died 26/07/2008, the daughter of the architect and craftsman C R (Charles Robert) Ashbee and his wife Janet Forbes.  Felicity Ashbee was an artist, designer, author and teacher.
